# RGB-D images
Images contain **apples** and **tennis balls**. Apples marked with a tag and a numeric-ID are those whose growth was monitored throughout the season.
1. **Color images (RGB)**:
   * dimensions: 1080 x 1920 x 3 (H x W x C)
   * data type: uint8
   * file format: `.png`

<img src=../dataset/1_0m/HIGH/2022_09_21/P1.png><br>

2. **Depth images (D)**: 
   * dimensions: 1080 x 1920 x 1 (H x W x C)
   * data type: float64
   * file format: `.npy`
   * u.d.m: meters [`m`]

# annotations
Image annotation files (`.json`) contain data in a JSON-based format, namely [supervisely format](https://docs.supervisely.com/customization-and-integration/00_ann_format_navi).

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<br>

Image objects have the following information:
| tag | description |
|---|---|
| "description" | (`string`) - if present, it indicates the ID of the target item to be matched with ground truth data |
| "labelerLogin" | (`string`) - it gives a description of the labelling method used to get the object bounding box |
| "classTitle" | (`string`) - class name: `apple_manual_annot`, `apple_Y5L_std_bbox`, `apple_Y5L_trained_bbox`, `TB_manual_annot`, `TB_Y5L_std_bbox`, `TB_Y5L_trained_bbox`|
| "exterior" | (`int`) - lis of `top-left`, `bottom-right` bbox coordinates|

<br>

# Ground truth
1. [Evaluation ground truth](data_ground_truth/evaluation_ground_truth_data.csv): reference growth data of monitored fruits (i.e., numeric IDs) and Tennis balls (literal IDs). Data were manually collected with a digital caliper and represent the main equatorial diameter of the monitored item. This dataset was cleaned to remove potential human-induced or sensor-induced errors. 
   * The dataset contains `NaN` values as showed in the [data exploration](notebook/data_exploration.ipynb) notebook.
   * in the columns, dates are in format *day / month / year*
   * number of items: 24 apples, 2 tennis balls

# Dataset structure
**Level 0**: dataset root\
**Level 1**: main folders (i.e. `1_0m`, `1_5m`) aggregating files according to the object-camera distance.\
**Level 2**: subfolders that contain images shot with the same tree perspective:
   + `HIGH` - meaning the image contains the top of the canopy, 
   + `LOW` - the image contains the bottom of the canopy, 
   + `FULL_TREE` - the image contains the whole canopy.
  
**Level 3**: folders of each sampling time\
**Level 4**: data files (i.e., `.png`, `.npy`, `.json`). The file nomenclature referes to the plant id:
<center>

| file | description|
|---|---|
|P1.* | file containing data referring to tree/plant number 1 |
|P2.* | file containing data referring to tree/plant number 2 |

</center>
